$\mu = \frac{\sum_{i}^N x_{i}}{N}$

Median¶

$Median = \frac{1}{2}(x[\frac{N}{2}]+x[\frac{N}{2}+1])$ for even N
$Median = x[int(\frac{N}{2})]$ for odd N

Variance¶

It is the expectation of the squared deviation of a random variable from its mean. Informally, it measures how far a set of numbers are spread out from their average value.

$\sigma^2 = \frac{\sum_{i}^N (x_{i}-\bar{x})^2}{N}$

In [225]:
from statistics import variance
var=variance(ages)
print(f"The variance of the ages list is {round(var,2)}")

The variance of the ages list is 18.67

Standard Deviation¶

It is the square root of the average of the squared deviations from the mean.
$\sigma = \sqrt(\frac{\sum_{i}^N (x_{i}-\bar{x})^2}{N})$

Quantiles¶

Refers to each of any set of values of a variate which divide a frequency distribution into equal groups, each containing the same fraction of the total population.

There are thre quartiles: Q1 is the median of the lower half (smaller than the median) of the population after it has been sorted in ascending order. Q2 is the same as the median of the population. Q3 is the median of the the upper half (greater than the median) of the population.

In [226]:
import numpy as np
Qs=np.quantile(ages,[0.25,0.5,0.75])
print(f"Q1 is {round(Qs[0],2)}, Q2 is {round(Qs[1],2)}, and Q3 is {round(Qs[2],2)}")

Q1 is 9.5, Q2 is 14.0, and Q3 is 16.5

Covariance¶

ovariance provides a measure of the strength of the correlation between two or more sets of random variates. The covariance for two random variates and , each with sample size , is defined by the expectation value.

$cov(X,Y)=cov(Y,X)=E<(X-\mu_{x})(Y-\mu_{y})>=<X><Y>-\mu_{x}\mu_{y}$
$cov(X,Y)=\frac{\sum_{i}^{N}((x_{i}-\mu_{x})(y_{i}-\mu_{y}))}{N}$

For uncorrelated variates: $cov(X,Y)=0$

However, if the variables are correlated in some way, then their covariance will be nonzero

Self-covariance is equal to the variance: $cov(X,X)=<X^2>-<X>^2=\sigma_{xx}^2$

Variance in terms of covariance
$Var(X+Y)=Var(X)+Var(Y)+2*cov(X,Y)$

$cov(X+Z,Y)=cov(X,Z)+cov(Z,Y)$

In [236]:
np.cov(ages,ages)
Out[236]:

       [18.67251462, 18.67251462]])

Correlation¶

A statistical measure that indicates the extent to which two or more variables fluctuate together. A positive correlation indicates the extent to which those variables increase or decrease in parallel; a negative correlation indicates the extent to which one variable increases as the other decreases.

$cor(X,Y)=\frac{cov(X,Y)}{\sigma_{X}\sigma_{y}}=\frac{\sigma_{xy}}{\sqrt(\sigma_{xx}\sigma_{yy})}$

In [245]:
np.corrcoef(x, y)
Out[245]:
array([[1.        , 0.97555732],
       [0.97555732, 1.        ]])
In [246]:

Kullback–Leibler divergence¶

In mathematical statistics, the Kullback–Leibler divergence (also called relative entropy) is a measure of how one probability distribution is different from a second, reference probability distribution. Applications include characterizing the relative (Shannon) entropy in information systems, randomness in continuous time-series, and information gain when comparing statistical models of inference.

For discrete probability distributions P and Q defined on the same probability space, the Kullback–Leibler divergence between P and Q is defined to be

#Log2  --> bits
import math
h1=[]
for i in range(len(x)):
    t=probx[i]*math.log2(probx[i]/proby[i])
    h1.append(t)
H1=sum(h1)
print(f"P||Q is {round(H1,2)}")

h2=[]
for i in range(len(x)):
    t=proby[i]*math.log2(proby[i]/probx[i])
    h2.append(t)
H2=sum(h2)
print(f"Q||P is {round(H2,2)}")

P||Q is 0.12
Q||P is 0.14
